package com.beaglebuddy.tab.gui.font;




/**
 * This class contains mnemonics for the music symbols defined in the supplementary unicode standard.
 * <p>
 * For this discussion, refer to the  definition of the U+n notation in the Unicode standard at http://www.unicode.org.
 * </p>
 * <p>
 * The java char data type is based on the original Unicode specification, which defined characters as fixed-width 16-bit entities.
 * The range of legal code points was thus U+0000 to U+FFFF, and is referred to as the Basic Multilingual Plane (BMP).
 * The Unicode standard has since been changed to allow for characters whose representation requires more than 16 bits.
 * The range of legal code points is now U+0000 to U+10FFFF, known as Unicode scalar value.
 * </p>
 * <p>
 * The set of characters from U+0000 to U+FFFF is sometimes referred to as the Basic Multilingual Plane (BMP).
 * The set of characters from U+10000 to U+10FFFF are called supplementary characters.
 * Since the java character type was based on the original unicode specification of fixed-width 16 bit characters, java is
 * not able to represent the supplementary unicode characters in the char data type.
 * However, java uses the UTF-16 representation in char arrays and in the String and StringBuffer classes, and is therefore
 * able to represent the supplementary unicode characters in these java types.
 * In this representation, supplementary characters are represented as a pair of char values, the first from the
 * high-surrogates range, (\uD800-\uDBFF), the second from the low-surrogates range (\uDC00-\uDFFF).
 * </p>
 * <p>
 * A java char value, therefore, represents Basic Multilingual Plane (BMP) code points.
 * A java int  value represents all Unicode code points, including supplementary code points., with the lower (least significant) 21 bits
 * of the int used to represent Unicode code points and the upper (most significant) 11 bits set to zero.
 * </p>
 */
